		<Row Tag="LOC_PEDIA_BUILDINGS_PAGE_BUILDING_GEDEMO_HAREPAENGA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1" Language="zh_Hans_CN">
			<Text>【译者注：正在翻译……】[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]The Hare Paenga, also known as boat houses, had volcanic stone foundations pierced with orifices which allowed a plant hull-like structure to be fixed upside down. Many vestiges of these dwellings are scattered all over Easter Island. The appearance of boat houses is known thanks to engravings by the writer Pierre Loti, made in 1872, on which he depicted the hare paenga of a Rapa Nui chief. These dwellings were reserved for dignitaries and their families. The rest of the clan probably lived in more basic huts without a stone foundation or in the many caves on Easter Island.</Text>
